The former private secretary to Nelson Mandela, Zelda La Grange, will be one of the judges in the Excellence In Education Awards 2018, specifically the #100Mandela category, iStore South Africa and Think Ahead announced yesterday. In order for any legacy to remain current, La Grange said, we have to provide the youth continuously and consistently with tools and skills to disseminate the legacy in an apt form. “This is a fun way for youngsters to be innovative about Madiba’s legacy, to learn and to create an appetite for history. I look forward to experiencing their creativity,” she said. The awards celebrate South African schools using Apple technology to transform teaching and learning. This year the awards introduced a special category to honour Madiba. Students were challenged to submit a two-minute video that must be innovative, and passionate. Other four categories include Curriculum Challenge; were teachers and students are given the freedom to apply creativity across any area of the curriculum, subjects and cross-curricular projects. Artistic Excellence; were students will have the opportunity to express themselves through the Arts.  The third is iTeacher. This calls for teachers to demonstrate how they have redeﬁned teaching and learning by using Apple technology, regularly within their classroom. And lastly is the Coding Challenge. This category offers the freedom to share an original app or website with the world. Winning teachers get a 6th Gen iPad and Beats EP, on-ear headphones deliver masterfully tuned sound, for winning students.    African News Agency